alse,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115439","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115439"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 75-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with his daughter due to worsening forgetfulness over the past two days. His daughter reports that prior to this episode, he had no memory or cognitive issues and was generally in good health. She is concerned that this forgetfulness came on acutely and is afraid he may no longer be able to care for himself independently. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He has a history of heavy alcohol use of five to six standard drinks daily for 20 years, but over the past three years has reduced his consumption to no more than two standard drinks daily. He lives at home alone and is usually independent for all activities of daily living.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. He is oriented to person and place but not to time. He has difficulty remembering names and recent events and is unable to give any clear history.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Alzheimer\u0027s dementia","Wernicke encephalopathy","Subdural haematoma","Delirium tremens","Korsakoff syndrome"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most likely diagnosis in this case is a \u003Cstrong\u003Esubdural haematoma\u003C/strong\u003E. SDH refers to bleeding within the intracranial subdural space, typically due to rupture of bridging veins. It can be caused by minor head trauma, which is particularly significant in older adults due to age-related brain atrophy. While no fall or head trauma is noted in the stem, it cannot be ruled out on history due to the patient\u0027s acute confusion and inability to recall recent events, as well as the fact that he lives alone (i.e. the fall would likely have been unwitnessed). The relatively short history in this case points to a traumatic cause being the most likely explanation for his present condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlzheimer\u0027s disease\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with a more insidious onset of cognitive decline over months to years, rather than the acute onset described in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWernicke encephalopathy\u003C/strong\u003E is an acute, reversible condition due to severe thiamine deficiency, often seen in chronic alcohol users. While this patient has a history of heavy alcohol use, he has reduced his intake significantly over the past three years and maintains a balanced diet. Moreover, Wernicke encephalopathy typically presents with confusion, ocular motor dysfunction, and gait ataxia, which are not described in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDelirium tremens\u003C/strong\u003E is a severe form of alcohol withdrawal syndrome, typically occurring 48-96 hours after the last drink in individuals with a history of chronic, heavy alcohol use. Given that this patient reduced his alcohol intake three years ago, delirium tremens is highly unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EKorsakoff syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is a chronic neurological condition resulting from thiamine deficiency, often seen as a late complication of chronic alcoholism. It typically develops gradually and is characterised by severe short-term memory loss and confabulation. The acute onset of symptoms and the patient\u0027s improved diet and reduced alcohol intake make Korsakoff syndrome less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn conclusion, the acute onset of cognitive symptoms, with the possibility of a recent head injury, in an elderly patient strongly suggests a subdural haematoma. Neuroimaging would be essential to confirm the diagnosis, typically showing a biconvex, concave lesion that may cross cranial suture lines. Prompt diagnosis and management are crucial to prevent further neurological deterioration.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Subdural haematoma can present with gradual cognitive decline and memory impairment days to weeks after minor head trauma, especially in older adults.","Chronic subdural haematoma should be considered in elderly patients with acute or subacute-onset of cognitive decline, particularly if there is a potential for a fall or head injury.","Neuroimaging is essential for diagnosing subdural haematoma, which appears as a biconvex, concave lesion that may cross cranial suture lines."],"references":["Gennarelli TA, Thibault LE. Biomechanics of acute subdural hematoma. J Trauma 1982; 22:680. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/7108984/","Yang W, Huang J. Chronic Subdural Hematoma: Epidemiology and Natural History. Neurosurg Clin N Am 2017; 28:205. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28325454/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97442"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"644"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97442","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97442"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-23T17:41:37+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-23T17:44:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"644"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115439"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"6","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/6"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc75","name":"Geriatrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji